                  Exhortation to Magiſtrates and Officers to doe their duties though the people do cauſleſly curſe them. And it is not vnprobable that ſome of you (worthy
Magiſtrates) for diligence in doing your duties,
and for your laudable endeuours to furniſh the
Markets by drawing forth the Corne out of the
bands of horders, and the hands of huckſters, ſhall
carry away ſome curſes from the mouches or in the
mindes, of theſe mizars. 'Tis not vnlikely, but that
ſome of them (ſuch is their charity) will reward
you with curſes, euen for this your care to preuent
the curſes of the people vpon them. But be not diſcouraged,
Salomon hath ſecured you againſt ſuch
airie execrations. Theſe breath-bullets ſhall not
pierce you; theſe Speares of Reed, and Swords of
Bull-ruſhes ſhall not ſo much as pricke your reputations,
much leſſe your conſciences.Such curſes ſhall not hurt their credits or conſciences, but rebound on thoſe who do vſe them. The bubbles of
ſuch curſes ſhall fall into the faces and eyes of thoſe
who blow them vp: like mad-men they runne at
you with the hilt, but the point of the ſword runneth
into their owne breſt. Let that bee your refuge
which was Dauids in the like caſe, euen flying
